  "text": "Such deletion and insertion operations are central to text simplification, but a few other operations are also needed to handle morphology and to avoid broken dependency links in the Target ETs. These are enumerated in [CITATION_1] . By collecting such rules, a meta-grammar is produced that can translate dependency parses in one language (English) into the other (simplified English). The rule above will translate \"most intensive\" to \"strongest\", in the immediate lexical context of \"storm\". The ET Transfer component can be presented either as transformation rules or as a transduction of ETs, as shown in Fig. 2 . In , we describe how such automatically acquired rules can be generalised to apply in new contexts; for instance, by expanding lexical context to include related words derived from WordNet, or by removing the lexical context for lexical simplifications that are not context dependent.",
